A f(A a) { return A(a.x+a.x); }; // this is ugly and I'd want to be able to use: return a+a

int main()
{
  A a = 5;
  B b = 5;
  f(a);     // This will work...
  f(b);     // This won't compile...
}
</code></pre>

<p><strong>My question is</strong> - what's the best way I can get code working like the 2nd snippet, but without having to explicitly getting <em>x</em> all the time and construct new objects (as noted in the line with the "this is ugly" comment)?</p>

